# Day 2 - Group-Based Access Control

## Task
Create the `nautilus_sftp_users` group on all App servers and add the user `rajesh` to that group. If the user does not exist, create it.

## Objective
Practice Linux group management, user creation, and access control across multiple servers.

## Commands Used
```bash
# connect to each app server
ssh tony@stapp01
ssh tony@stapp02
ssh tony@stapp03

# create group if it does not exist
sudo groupadd nautilus_sftp_users

# create user if needed
sudo useradd rajesh

# add user to group
sudo useradd -G nautilus_sftp_users rajesh

# verify
id rajesh
getent group nautilus_sftp_users
```

## What I Learned
- How groups simplify access management in Linux
- How to create and verify a user account
- How to add an existing user to a supplementary group
- Why group-based control is useful in multi-server environments

## Personal Notes
This task reinforced the importance of checking the existing system state before making changes. It also showed how Linux groups are used to keep access management consistent across servers.
